    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "Ancestor of Hanan, who assisted Nehemiah. Neh. 13:\n10. The three Persons are also named in the formula instituted by Christ in baptism. Matt. 28:\n10. Troas. [Tro'as] Seaport town and district in Mysia, in the north-west of Asia Minor: it was visited by Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` on his journeys to and from Macedonia. On one occasion he abode there seven days, and raised Eutychus to life when, the disciples having come together 'to break bread,' Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` preached till midnight. Acts 16: 8, 11; Acts 20: 5, 6; 2 Cor. 2: 12; 2 Tim. 4:\n10. Truth is the real way of liberty: &quot;the truth shall make you free.&quot; John `[char_John_Ref]` 8: 32,\n10. The name is Greek, and nothing is said of Tyrannus being a disciple, so that the Christians may have hired the 'school,' as halls are rented in the present day. Tyre, Tyrus. Seaport in Lebanon (peviously Syria), about midway between Sidon and Accho. It was a place of great commerce, sending to the East by land and to the West by the sea. This is shown to have been the case in several of the prophets. It was not conquered by the Israelites, and is first spoken of when its king Hiram sent to David `[char_David_Rut_4]` cedar trees with carpenters and masons to build David `[char_David_Rut_4]` a house. 2 Sam. 5: 11; 1 Chr. 14:",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "is clearly the Second Advent with no other interpretation allowed, but no Jewish Rabbi or Hebrew scholar could make heads or tails out of the passage because they all have an instinctive, programmed, built-in tendency to omit the Second Coming of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. I thought before moving on to \u201cthe garden of NUTS\u201d in the next verse, that it would be appropriate to give you a sampling of a typical, rotten piece of exegesis put out by the Scholars\u2019 Union. In this case, it was put out by Jamieson, Fausset, and Brown; they had no more idea of how to handle the passage than any other Biblical illiterate in the Alexandrian Cult. According to Jamieson, Fausset, and Brown, \u201cthe morning\u201d is the Church not coming to the fullness of her light. \u201cThe sun\u201d isn\u2019t Christ at all; it\u2019s the light of the Church\u2019s justification. They get the cross-reference to Matthew 13:42 for \u201cthe sun,\u201d but when they got to the \u201carmy,\u201d they fell all to pieces. Jamieson, Fausset, and Brown applied the term to starry angelic hosts which they leave unidentified. They refer you to Revelation 12:1 for the \u201carmy,\u201d which is a perfect blank. Finally, when interpreting the whole verse, they say the Church Triumphant (an old-time reference to the saints in Heaven) is the bannered \u201carmy,\u201d the Adventical Church is likened to \u201cthe sun,\u201d and the Levitical Church is likened to \u201cthe moon.\u201d That is the mess into which you get with a non-scriptural exegesis based on opinions and preferences. That\u2019s the \u201cscholarship\u201d of every scholar in the Nineteenth, Twentieth, and Twenty-first Centuries who attempted to correct the King James text. They\u2019re all \u201cbirds of a feather\u201d\u2014cuckoos.\nverse 10 is clearly the Second Advent with no other interpretation allowed, but no Jewish Rabbi or Hebrew scholar could make heads or tails out of the passage because they all have an instinctive, programmed, built-in tendency to omit the Second Coming of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. I thought before moving on to \u201cthe garden of NUTS\u201d in the next verse, that it would be appropriate to give you a sampling of a typical, rotten piece of exegesis put out by the Scholars\u2019 Union. In this case, it was put out by Jamieson, Fausset, and Brown; they had no more idea of how to handle the passage than any other Biblical illiterate in the Alexandrian Cult. According to Jamieson, Fausset, and Brown, \u201cthe morning\u201d is the Church not coming to the fullness of her light. \u201cThe `[group_Word_Luk_1]` sun\u201d isn\u2019t Christ at all; it\u2019s the light of the Church\u2019s justification. They get the cross-reference to [v_Mat_13_42] Matthew 13:42 for \u201cthe sun,\u201d but when they got to the \u201carmy,\u201d they fell all to pieces. Jamieson, Fausset, and Brown applied the term to starry angelic hosts which they [v_Rev_12_1] leave unidentified. They refer you to Revelation 12:1 for the \u201carmy,\u201d which is a perfect blank. Finally, when interpreting the whole verse, they say the Church Triumphant (an old-time reference to the saints in Heaven) is the bannered \u201carmy,\u201d the Adventical Church is likened to \u201cthe sun,\u201d and the Levitical Church is likened to \u201cthe moon.\u201d That is the mess into which you get with a non- scriptural exegesis based on opinions and preferences. That\u2019s the \u201cscholarship\u201d of every scholar in the Nineteenth, Twentieth, and Twenty-first Centuries who attempted to correct the King James text. They\u2019re all \u201cbirds of a feather\u201d\u2014cuckoos.",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "But the men put forth their hand, etc.] They came to the door, and opened it, and put out their hands, one on one side the door, and the other on the other: 344 and pulled Lot into the house to them, and shut to the door; and thus they rescued Lot from the fury and rage of the men of Sodom, and prevented his daughters being exposed unto them, as he had offered. This action showed them to be more than men, that they should open the door, take in Lot, and shut it so suddenly, that the men of Sodom could take no advantage of it, could neither retain Lot, nor enter the door when opened, and especially what follows.\nVer."
